# Knowledge Base Conventions

This file is read by Claude at the start of every knowledge skill invocation.
Do not delete it. Edit it as your knowledge base evolves.

---

## Directory Structure

```
~/knowledge/
├── raw/          # Source material inbox — LLM reads but rarely edits these
│   ├── articles/ # Web articles, blog posts (YYYY-MM-DD-<slug>.md)
│   ├── papers/   # PDFs or transcripts of research papers
│   ├── notes/    # Quick-capture notes from sessions (no source URL required)
│   └── images/   # Screenshots, diagrams
├── wiki/         # LLM-compiled knowledge — do not edit manually
│   ├── _index.md # Master index (categorized, one line per article)
│   ├── log.md    # Append-only activity log (ingest/compile/query/lint entries)
│   ├── _meta/    # Lint reports and health metadata
│   └── <topic>/  # One directory per concept cluster
└── outputs/      # Rendered deliverables
    ├── reports/  # Q&A outputs (YYYY-MM-DD-<slug>.md)
    └── slides/   # Marp slideshows
```

---

## Front Matter Fields

Every file in `raw/articles/` and `raw/papers/` must have YAML front matter:

```yaml
---
title: "Article Title"
source: "https://original-url.com"
date: "YYYY-MM-DD"
tags: [tag1, tag2]
status: unprocessed   # unprocessed | compiled | stub | draft | complete
---
```

Files in `raw/notes/` use a lighter front matter (no `source:` required):

```yaml
---
title: "Note title or observation"
date: "YYYY-MM-DD"
tags: [tag1, tag2]
status: unprocessed
type: note
---
```

Every file in `wiki/` must have YAML front matter:

```yaml
---
title: "Concept Name"
tags: [tag1, tag2]
status: complete      # stub | draft | complete
sources:
  - raw/articles/YYYY-MM-DD-slug.md
---
```

Wiki articles synthesized from queries (not backed by a raw source) use `sources: [synthesized]`.

---

## `_index.md` Format

Entries are grouped by category. One line per article:

```markdown
## Concepts
- [[topic/concept]] — One-sentence summary. (source: raw/articles/slug.md)

## Entities
- [[topic/specific-tool]] — One-sentence summary. (source: raw/articles/slug.md)

## Syntheses
- [[topic/analysis]] — Synthesized from query on YYYY-MM-DD.

## Sources
- [[topic/source-summary]] — Summary of a specific source document.
```

**Category definitions:**
- **Concepts** — general ideas, techniques, strategies, patterns
- **Entities** — specific named things: tools, models, frameworks, systems (e.g. ZeRO optimizer, Claude Code)
- **Syntheses** — articles created from query answers filed back into the wiki
- **Sources** — summary articles for specific source documents (optional, use sparingly)

The `_index.md` is the LLM's map of the entire wiki. Keep it accurate and complete.
Every wiki article must have exactly one entry here. Orphans and missing entries are lint errors.

---

## `log.md` Format

`wiki/log.md` is an **append-only** chronological record of all knowledge base operations.
Each entry starts with a parseable prefix — do not reformat existing entries.

```markdown
## [YYYY-MM-DD] ingest | Article Title
Source: https://...
Tags: tag1, tag2
Files: raw/articles/YYYY-MM-DD-slug.md (N images)

## [YYYY-MM-DD] compile | N docs processed
  - raw/articles/YYYY-MM-DD-slug.md → wiki/topic/concept.md (new)
  - raw/articles/YYYY-MM-DD-slug2.md → wiki/topic/concept2.md (updated)

## [YYYY-MM-DD] query | "Question text"
Output: inline | report: outputs/reports/YYYY-MM-DD-slug.md | wiki: wiki/topic/concept.md

## [YYYY-MM-DD] lint | N articles, X critical, Y warnings
Report: wiki/_meta/lint-report.md

## [YYYY-MM-DD] note | Note title
Filed: raw/notes/YYYY-MM-DD-slug.md
```

Parse the last 5 entries with: `grep "^## \[" ~/knowledge/wiki/log.md | tail -5`

---

## Wikilink Format

Use Obsidian `[[wikilink]]` syntax for all internal links (not markdown href syntax).
This enables Obsidian's graph view and backlink detection.

- Link to a concept: `[[topic/concept]]`
- Link with display text: `[[topic/concept|display text]]`

Every article must have a `## See Also` section at the bottom with wikilinks to related concepts.

---

## Topic Directory Naming

- Lowercase, hyphenated: `machine-learning`, `distributed-systems`, `product-design`
- Broad concept clusters — prefer fewer, broader topics over many narrow ones
- Each topic directory has an `index.md` summarising the topic and listing all articles in it

---

## Domain Topics (Agentic Development Focus)

This knowledge base is focused on agentic software development. When assigning topics,
prefer these clusters (create new subtopics as needed):

```
agentic-development/
  agent-patterns        — types of agents, orchestration strategies, when to use subagents
  context-management    — token budgets, context compaction, window management
  tool-usage            — MCP tools, Bash, Claude Code capabilities and quirks
  prompt-engineering    — system prompts, skill design, CLAUDE.md/AGENTS.md conventions
  workflow-patterns     — automation hooks, scheduled tasks, agentic pipelines

machine-learning/       — LLM internals, training, scaling, architectures
coding-agents/          — harness architectures, agent components, coding agent research
```

Use `agentic-development/` as the default home for insights about building or using
agentic systems, agent configurations, and Claude Code–specific knowledge.

---

## Article Length & Style

- Target: under 500 words per article unless the concept genuinely requires more
- Write in present tense, encyclopedic style
- Lead with a one-sentence definition of the concept
- Never delete content — archive superseded sections with `> [Archived: YYYY-MM-DD]`

---

## Compile Behaviour

When a raw document spans multiple topics:
1. Create one **primary** article in the most relevant topic directory
2. Add `## See Also` wikilinks from related topic articles pointing to the primary
3. Do not duplicate content across articles — cross-link instead

When updating an existing wiki article with new information from a raw doc:
1. Merge new information into the existing article
2. Add the new source to the article's `sources:` front matter list
3. Update the one-line summary in `_index.md` if it has changed

---

## PDF Workflow (if applicable)

If PDFs become a significant source type, consider Zotero + Zotero2MD plugin to export
highlights and annotations as structured markdown into `raw/papers/`. See the plan at
`~/dev/agentic-home/plans/knowledge-base.md` for details.
